COMITALE  LEO <comital@ecf.toronto.edu> wrote:

>I not only use my system, I actually INSTALL APPLICATIONS (besides
>uptime, of course).

   Bully for you.

   Even including installing applications, my admin work comes out
to be about 15 minutes a week.  And my system is completely
customised; it is based on MCC 1.0+, which was installed at least
a year ago.

   If you're seized with a obsession to always have the latest and
greatest, I can certainly see how this might get to the point of
absurdity, but if you follow the rule of don't upgrade anything
until you need to, life on Linux, as it is on any other operating
system, becomes a whole bunch easier.  (Though my MS-Windows admin
hours/week has finally dropped below 15 minutes a week. It's
because I only boot into Windows every other week now, but still,
it's an accomplisment.  Pity OS/2 never reached that point -- my
frustration with the inadequacies of the product led to it being
replaced with Windows months ago.)


>[...] , it's not how
>much you reboot, it's how often you have to exert energy to have
>things work the way you want.

   If your ideal environment is CP/M-80, _anything_ else will have
to be worked on to make it work like CP/M-80.  If your ideal
environment is OS/2, _anything_ else will have to be worked on to
make it work like OS/2.   You have the choice, though; either stick
with CP/M-80 or OS/2 or learn to deal with the small problem that
all systems are different.

