>I don't use GCC under OS/2, I use VisualAge C++, but I have used
>and installed a lot of free/share ware stuff for both systems and
>I find the OS/2 stuff easier to install/maintain.

Have you found a lot of variation in the ease of installation among
the freeware stuff?  I'd expect shareware to be a little easier to
install simply because they're actually expecting you to send them
money.  :-)

>If this is because
>I am not a Unix "guru" then so be it, but I don't see why I have to
>be one just to use the system.

I agree.  You must realize that Unix is traditionally a multiuser
system, and it's expected that there will be a person who specializes
in maintaining the system.  The normal users shouldn't need to know
anything Unix-specific to use the system (and, I might add, my fiancee
*doesn't* have to know anything Unix-specific to use Linux, largely
thanks to xfm and some work on my part, which includes modifications
to xfm).

I guess my point is that, in traditional Unix, there's a distinction
between using the system and maintaining it.  On a single-user system,
there usually isn't such a distinction (though in most companies,
users typically don't do any installations themselves anyway...there's
a technical staff there to do that).

OS/2 is relatively easy to maintain because it's a single-user system,
so there isn't any implicit assumption that there will be a
knowledgeable administrator available to do installation work.


Note, too, that there are certain flavors of Unix, e.g. Irix, for
which installation of software is usually easy unless you're compiling
it from the source.  Irix includes a special set of tools for
maintaining the installed base of software on the system.

>>What Linux needs to solve this particular problem is a single
>>installation and package management program that has All The Right
>>Stuff (GUI, version tracking, dependency management, etc), so that
>>commercial vendors can count on the thing existing.  *That* would make
>>application installs painless under Linux.  Unless, of course, you
>>were talking about freeware, in which case it would depend on whether
>>or not the author decided to use the package format that such a
>>program supported.
>
>I think having a statdard set of tools for developing applications
>would also help, rather than having all these programs which use
>various libraries and such as they do now.

Certain tools tend to become standard over time.  For instance, Tcl/Tk
is becoming one such standard...it's becoming harder to find systems
that don't have it.  It's becoming so widespread that some commercial
vendors make it available themselves.  Perl is another such example.

>It would solve a lot
>of the "version"-itis which Linux seems to be so susceptible to.
>Of course this would be difficult to accomplish as one of Linux's
>main strengths is it's openness which also happens to be why it
>has these problems in the first place...someone always thinks of
>a "better way".

Yup, I agree.  And part of the reason that so much of the freeware for
Linux is relatively high-quality is that it depends on later rather
than earlier versions of external libraries.  The later versions of
libraries tend to have fewer bugs...

Additionally, freeware under Unix is generally distributed as source
because it's generally designed to run under many different platforms,
whereas under OS/2 it's probably distributed as binaries.  A binary
distribution is a lot easier to deal with than a source
distribution...

If OS/2 were available on a plethora of incompatible platforms, I'd
expect that most freeware would be distributed as source and you'd end
up with many of the same problems that you have under Linux (or binary
distributions would become unwieldy)...

>Thanks for an intelligent reply.

My pleasure.  :-)

